('Automotive cabin soak temperature control strategies for improved safety, comfort and energy efficiency', 349, 'bassani.marco@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['mutani.guglielmina@tmtest.polito.it']::text[], ARRAY['AUTOMOTIVE CABIN','CLIMATE CONTROL STRATEGY','DRIVER BEHAVIOR','ENERGY CONSUMPTION','LIGHTING CONDITIONS','MONITORING SYSTEM','ROAD SAFETY AND ACCIDENTS','SPACE HEATING AND COOLING','THERMAL COMFORT','VEHICLE SIMULATOR']::text[], 'Tesi di Laurea', ARRAY['LM-28 group 1']::text[], 'There has been growing concern over achieving rapid cabin thermal comfort upon entering a hot/cold-soaked vehicle, thereby reducing occupant stress and discomfort. These conditions impact when drinving or parking under direct sunlight or in extra cold air temperatures. There is a correlation between climate parameters and drivers'' fatigue. Performing complex tasks under cold/hot stress is shown to result in increased errors which may reflect on safety. It has been found that cabin temperature threatens children and pets, leading to discomfort upon entry and reaching deadly levels. The most feasible passive technologies include implementing solar chimneys, aluminium covers, solar-powered ventilation, and reflective glass. The colour of the car’s bodywork should also be considered, as it has a significant impact on reducing or inrease the cabin air temperature. The choice of technology depends on factors such as energy fuel, economic feasibility, end-user behaviour, and government regulations.

', ARRAY[]::text[], 'Vedi anche: the cold driver_ driving performance under thermal stress.pdf', '2024-10-11', 2, ARRAY['LM-28 - Master Degree in Electrical Engineering']::text[]),
('Uso di modellazione multiscale e intelligenza artificiale per la digitalizzazione dell''industria farmaceutica, alimentare e dei prodotti per la cura della persona', 5, 'buffo.antonio@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['marchisio.daniele@tmtest.polito.it']::text[], ARRAY['ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE','ARTIFICIAL NEURAL NETWORK','DINAMICA MOLECOLARE','DISSIPATIVE PARTICLE DYNAMICS','FLUIDODINAMICA COMPUTAZIONALE','MACHINE LEARNING']::text[], 'MODELLISTICA E SIMULAZIONE', ARRAY['Aa - Multiscale Modelling For Materials Science And Process Engineering']::text[], 'Numerosi processi dell''industria farmaceutica, alimentare e dei prodotti per la cura della persona possono essere simulati con tecniche di modellazione multiscala e intelligenza artificiale. La loro simulazione permette di ottimizzarli in modo efficiente in modo da ridurre consumi energetici e utilizzo di materie prime, rendendoli quindi più sostenibili. Con questa tesi si vogliono studiare in particolare processi che coinvolgono fluidi strutturati, quali emulsioni (ad es. emulsioni alimentari e farmaceutiche) e soluzioni concentrate di tensioattivi, sistemi colloidali (ad es. polimerici o lipidici) per il rilascio controllato di farmaci, inclusi sistemi a m-RNA. Le tecniche utilizzate sono la dinamica molecolare classica e "coarse-grained", la fluidodinamica computazionale e i bilanci di popolazione, nonché intelligenza artificiale.', ARRAY[]::text[], '', '2024-09-27', 2, ARRAY['LM-07 - Master Degree in Agricultural Biotechnology','LM-28 - Master Degree in Electrical Engineering']::text[]),
('Metodi di disegno sperimentale/machine learning nel campo energetico', 55, 'bella.federico@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['pugliese.diego@tmtest.polito.it']::text[], ARRAY['BATTERIE','ENERGIA','FOTOVOLTAICO','FUEL CELL','SCAMBIO TERMICO','CFD','MACHINE LEARNING']::text[], 'COMPILATIVA', ARRAY['Electrochemistry Group @Polito']::text[], 'Batterie, celle fotovoltaiche, fuel cell e supercapacitori rappresentano i dispositivi con cui l''uomo gestisce (e gestirà sempre di più) la propria quotidianità. Questi dispositivi funzionano grazie ad un''ottima commistione di diversi componenti e all''ingegnerizzazione dal punto di vista chimico, dei materiali ed energetico. In campo accademico, lo studio dei vari parametri che andranno ad influenzare le prestazioni dei suddetti dispositivi viene fatto mediante tecniche di experimental design (disegno sperimentale), organizzando gli esperimenti e le prove di funzionamento tramite software commerciali o sviluppati negli atenei.
Questa tesi compilativa prevede la stesura di un documento in lingua inglese a partire da una collezione di articoli scientifici (forniti dal relatore) sul tema dell''experimental design applicato in campo energetico. Verrà scelto (insieme allo studente) un tema tra i 4 citati sopra e lo studente sarà chiamato a sviluppare un documento compilativo che racconti gli studi fatti sul tema scelto e come l''experimental design è stato utilizzato per ottimizzare il dispositivo energetico.

', ARRAY['Capacità di leggere e scrivere in inglese. Volontà di concludere la tesi entro 6 mesi dall''inizio.']::text[], 'Vedi anche: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Design_of_experiments', '2024-10-12', 2, ARRAY['LM-32 - Master Degree in Computer Engineering','LM-13 - Master Degree in Pharmacy and Industrial Pharmacy']::text[]),
('Modeling Online Social Networks Interactions', 131, 'leonardi.emilio@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['vassio.luca@tmtest.polito.it','Michele Garetto','Unito
Franco Galante','Polito']::text[], ARRAY['BIG DATA','DATA SCIENCE','MODELLAZIONE','RETI SOCIALI']::text[], 'DATA ANALYSIS, MODELLING', ARRAY['Database And Data Mining Group - Dbdm','Smartdata@Polito','Telecommunication Networks Group']::text[], 'Online social networks, such as Instagram and Facebook, allow users to interact and debate with each other. In this reserarch, the candidate will analyze large quantities of data collected from social networks, possibily using big data techniques (such as Pyspark). Then, the student will model the phenomena that characterize the usage of the social network. Finally, these models will be validated and will help recognizing the differences in usage and forecast possible future scenarios.', ARRAY['Modellazione, analisi dati, big data (pyspark)']::text[], '', '2024-09-30', 2, ARRAY['LM-18 - Master Degree in Computer Science','LM-20 - Master Degree in Aerospace and Astronautical Engineering','LM-09 - Master Degree in Medical, Veterinary, and Pharmaceutical Biotechnology']::text[]),
('DESIGN AND DEVELOPMENT OF MODULAR SENSOR SEATS FOR AUTONOMOUS VEHICLES', 11, 'scattina.alessandro@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['Prof. Alberto Vergnano (Università Degli Studi Di Modena E Reggio Emilia)']::text[], ARRAY[' the ']::text[], 'NUMERICA E PROGETTUALE', ARRAY['25-Struttura E Sicurezza Dei Veicoli: Progettazione','Simulazione','Ottimizzazione']::text[], 'The goal of the thesis is to improve the design, and consequently the Technology Readiness Level – TRL, of a seat equipped with a pressure sensor system to be used in the new autonomous vehicles. To improve the design of the system, simulations with Finite Element Method and Human Body Models will be used. These instruments will be useful to study non-conventional posture allowed with the autonomous vehicles. The simulations will be used to optimize the layout of the sensors in order to increase accuracy and reliability of the system.
More details about the topic of the thesis can be found below.
Scientific researchers and automotive industries are developing the technologies for the future connected and autonomous vehicles. According to SAE International Standard J3016, in levels 4, High Automation and 5, Full Automation, the attention demanded to the driver and occupants is progressively relaxed, allowing them to engage in non-driving activities in non-conventional positions. However, in case of accident the airbag deployment against an Out of Position (OOP) occupant may cause serious injuries instead of mitigating the crash effects. To this aim, the car manufacturers carry out severe crash tests for the airbag deployment against OOP dummies, including both driver and passengers. The safety of the future “intelligent” vehicles may be improved by developing airbag systems adaptive to the car speed, impact severity, safety belt use, body size and on the actual occupant position. So, future intelligent vehicles should be also able of monitoring the inside scenario with physical and physiological measurements.
The occupant position can be studied for ergonomics or safety purposes by monitoring the occupant pressure on the seat surface. To this goal, 3 prototypes have already been developed:
1. a sensorized seat cover with 16 Force Sensing Resistors and controlled with Arduino system;
2. a pressure mat with 1500 cells made up of a piezoresistive sheet and a row x column logic;
3. a seat subdivided in 13 modules sensorized with load cells controlled with Arduino system or with STM board.
With these prototypes (papers available upon request) the feasibility of a pressure sensor system for detecting OOP conditions of the occupants has been demonstrated. The pressure field is evaluated against the dynamics of the vehicle, considered as a mobile reference platform, monitored by an Inertial Measurement Unit (IMU). The intelligent seat system is therefore able to identify whether the movements of the pressure centre are due to the accelerations or to the change of position of the occupant towards an OOP.', ARRAY[]::text[], '', '2024-06-20', 1, ARRAY['L-40 - Sociology','L-05 - Philosophy','L-24 - Psychological Sciences and Techniques']::text[]),
('Development of a neural network for Critical Heat Flux predictions', 492, 'pedroni.nicola@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY['coherence and exploitability']::text[], 'Tesi all''estero', ARRAY['Nemo']::text[], '- Title of the research
Development of a neural network for Critical Heat Flux predictions
(duration: around 6 months, starting period: can be discussed, but around September 2023)
 - Context of the research
The Critical Heat Flux (CHF) is a physical phenomenon that may cause the deterioration of the heat transfer in the core of nuclear reactors, potentially leading to core damage. Its accurate prediction is therefore a crucial issue in nuclear reactor safety. 
 - Objectives of the research
The proposed thesis concerns the development of a neural network to predict the occurrence of the CHF. It will be realized in preparation of an international OECD/NEA project on the development and application of Artificial Intelligence methodologies for nuclear engineering.
 - Work phases
Within this framework, the intern will: 
*Perform a preliminary literature review on artificial intelligence methodologies. 
*Analyze the available experimental CHF database to understand the physical phenomenon and to verify the coherence and exploitability of the experimental data. 
*Develop a neural network to predict as accurately as possible the CHF. Different approaches (e.g. different split in training and validation database, number of neurons) will be tested to determine the optimal solution. 
*Compare the performance of the newly developed neural networks against the existing models and identify the advantage/disadvantages associated to the usage of artificial intelligence. 
*Present and discuss his/her work during technical meetings and write a final report.
 POSSIBILITY OF INTERNSHIP (TO BE DISCUSSED, NOT MANDATORY)
- Internship/company description
The internship work will be conducted at the Department of Thermal-hydraulics and Fluid dynamics (STMF – Service de Thermohydraulique et de Mécanique de Fluide) within the Energy Division (DES - Direction des Énergies). The department develops and qualifies the simulation tools for the design and the safety analysis of the French nuclear power systems, such as the system thermal-hydraulic code CATHARE. These studies are performed within the framework of internal CEA projects or in collaboration with several industrial partners (e.g. EDF, Framatome and TechnicAtome) and international partners.
 For further information, please contact:
Prof. Nicola Pedroni (nicola.pedroni@tmtest.polito.it)

