('Measurement of audio-video ecological scenes for the Audio Space Lab of the Politecnico di Torino.', 325, 'astolfi.arianna@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['carlomasoero.marco@tmtest.polito.it','shtrepi.louena@tmtest.polito.it','Giuseppina Emma Puglisi']::text[], ARRAY['ACOUSTICS','VIRTUAL REALITY']::text[], 'EXPERIMENTAL', ARRAY['Tebe']::text[], 'The thesis will aim to the in-field recording of ecological audio and video scenes for the Audio Space Lab of the Politecnico di Torino. Ecological acoustical scenes will emulate everyday living environments, with acoustical conditions ranging from almost anechoic and quiet, to very reverberant and noisy. In-field measurements will be carried out by the innovative Multiple Input Multiple Output (MIMO) technique. The MIMO method relies on a multi-channel source prototype, specifically designed by the University of Parma, to simulate different directivity patterns (a speaker, a group of speakers, an equipment, etc.), inside the room, and on a commercial multi-capsule microphone recording in the High Order Ambisonic (HOA) format, able to thoroughly capture the directivity of the emitted sound. 
The audio rendering platform in the ASL will rely on the High Order Ambisonic (HOA) technique for the sound field reproduction, so as to reconstruct the 3D sound feeling at the listener’s ears, leveraging on a highly accurate sound spatiality. In addition, visual cues, reproduced through an adequate video rendering system, will support the audio simulation, so emulating in the whole the real contexts in which speech comprehension is usually required.', ARRAY[]::text[], '', '2024-04-22', 2, ARRAY['LM-17 - Master Degree in Physics','LM-21 - Master Degree in Biomedical Engineering','LM-08 - Master Degree in Industrial Biotechnology']::text[]),
('Sviluppo di algoritmi di guida per manovre di assetto di piccoli satelliti', 261, 'capello.elisa@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[' su ','Sviluppo',' di ']::text[], 'Tesi di Laurea', ARRAY['08- Dinamica','Controllo E Simulazione Del Volo']::text[], 'Sviluppo di algoritmi di guida, basati su potenziali artificiali per assetto di satelliti. Algoritmi "ottimizzati" per ridurre il tempo di manovra.', ARRAY[]::text[], '', '2024-04-26', 2, ARRAY['LM-13 - Master Degree in Pharmacy and Industrial Pharmacy','LM-30 - Master Degree in Energy and Nuclear Engineering']::text[]),
('Modelli matematici in biomedicina.', 33, 'edoardodelitala.marcello@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY['particolare equazioni differenziali',' di ','alla']::text[], 'Tesi di Laurea', ARRAY['L-34 group 2']::text[], 'Sviluppo e analisi di modelli matematici in biomedicina. Sono sviluppate applicazioni legate alla biologia e alla medicina, quali la dinamica di sistemi multicellulari tumorali, il ruolo di specifici agenti terapeutici e l''emergenza della resistenza ai farmaci, aspetti di motilità cellulare e processi di crescita tissutale e neoplastica, il ruolo del micro-ambiente tumorale nel determinare l''eterogeneita'' fenotipica, fenomeni di selezione Darwiniana nella tumorigenesi. L''argomento specifico viene concordato con il tesista.
 Il formalismo matematico tipicamente usato è quello della dinamica delle popolazioni e delle popolazioni con struttura interna e in particolare equazioni differenziali, integro-differenziali e PDE. 
 Oltre alla parte modellistica, in funzione delle inclinazioni del tesista, viene essere effettuata una analisi qualitativa e/o computazionale per evidenziare l?aderenza alla realtà del modello proposto, sottolineando eventuali comportamenti emergenti.', ARRAY[]::text[], '', '2024-10-12', 1, ARRAY['L-34 - Geological Sciences']::text[]),
('Testing delay faults on asynchronous reset signals', 178, 'cantoro.riccardo@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['sonzareorda.matteo@tmtest.polito.it','Michelangelo Grosso']::text[], ARRAY['TESTING','VLSI']::text[], 'Tesi esterna in azienda', ARRAY['Dauin - Gr-05 - Electronic Cad & Reliability Group - Cad']::text[], 'This thesis will be performed in the joint laboratory between PoliTo and STMciroelectronics existing withing PoliTo. 
The activities will focus on a specific but very relevant topic raising practical issues in the test of current circuits manufactured by STMicroelectronics, i.e., the test of delay faults affecting the reset circuitry. These faults are not easily managed by current EDA tools. 
The thesis activity will be organized in the following phases
1 - problem understanding, resorting to some test cases
2 - analysis of the solutions provided by current EDA tools (in particular, by Synopsys and Mentor)
3 - development of solutions to properly manage these faults
4 - solution assessment on real circuits by STMicroelectronics.
STMicroelectronics offers a grant for the student involved in the thesis.
In the recent past, most of the students involved in a master thesis with STMicroelectronics have been offered for a position in the company.', ARRAY['Basic knowledge in digital design and testing']::text[], '', '2024-03-05', 1, ARRAY['L-30 - Physical Sciences and Technologies']::text[]),
('Preparazione di nanoparticelle magnetiche a base di ferro disperse in matrici zeolitiche come catalizzatori innovativi per la purificazione di acque industriali', 510, 'esposito.serena@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['tammaro.olimpia@tmtest.polito.it']::text[], ARRAY[' Tali catalizzatori sono applicati',' di ']::text[], 'Tesi di Laurea', ARRAY['Aa - Surf-Chem']::text[], 'Zeoliti ultrastsabili ad alto rapporto Si/Al sono selezionate per modifiche post sintesi allo scopo di disperdere nanoparticelle magnetiche  base ferro. Tali catalizzatori sono applicati alla purificazioni di acque industriali', ARRAY[]::text[], '', '2024-07-03', 1, ARRAY['L-15 - Tourism Sciences','L-16 - Administration and Organization Sciences']::text[]),
('Parametric modelling of wave energy converters via data-based interpolation/extrapolation', 470, 'ezequielfaedo.nicolas@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY['CONTROL SYSTEMS','MODELLING','SYSTEM DYNAMICS','WAVE ENERGY - HYDRODYNAMICS - NUMERICAL MODELLING']::text[], 'MASTER THESIS', ARRAY['More Lab _ Http://Www.Morenergylab.Polito.It']::text[], 'Optimisation of ocean wave energy conversion systems, commonly referred to as wave energy
converters (WECs), can be an intricate process, which requires simultaneous evaluation of various
parameters of a given conversion concept in order to maximise productivity and, ultimately, minimise
final costs associated with the device. Such an optimisation process is commonly based on mathematical
models representing the device dynamics, in an attempt to predict performance behaviour, design
adequate control systems, and assess final productivity.
 Dynamical models for WEC systems are virtually always computed in terms of so-called boundary
element methods (BEMs), which provide, for a given (fixed) geometry, a characterisation of the
hydrodynamics of such a device. Though highly versatile, BEM-based software potentially necessitates a
substantial computational time to determine the hydrodynamics of an associated geometry with a given
degree of resolution, hence being less than ideal for iterative procedures, such as those normally
employed within performance optimization (see diagram below).
 Since geometry can be a key parameter within optimisation of WEC design, and BEM models are shape-dependent,
fast and reliable numerical modelling for different geometries is of paramount importance
to achieve efficient iterative loops for performance enhancement. In the light of this requirement, and
based on finite-dimensional output data computed with BEM codes, this project will aim at providing
interpolation-based techniques to tackle efficient WEC modelling for use within optimisation
procedures. Static and dynamic structures will be considered for interpolation (and extrapolation) of
hydrodynamics, based on standard techniques from the field of function approximation.

