('CAN vehicle Network IDS using Neural Network', 475, 'dicarlo.stefano@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['savino.alessandro@tmtest.polito.it','Obert Franco']::text[], ARRAY['AUTHENTICATION','AUTOMOTIVE','CAN NETWORK','IDENTITY MANAGEMENT','INTRUSION DETECTION','NEURAL NETWORKS','SECURITY']::text[], 'APPLICATIVA, RICERCA APPLICATA, RICERCA SPERIMENTALE, SVILUPPO HARDWARE', ARRAY['Dauin - Gr-24 - Smilies - Resilient Computer Architectures And Life Sci']::text[], 'Automotive connectivity is no longer an afterthought. With the growth of complex customer features, the automotive Electronic Control Units (ECUs) are increasing their connectivity ability, not only Vehicle-to-Vehicle (V2V) but also Vehicle-to-Everything (V2X). In this condition, the automotive market is becoming the perfect playground for hackers who want to exploit in-vehicle network protocols’ vulnerabilities. The primary automotive communication protocol is the Controller Area Network (CAN). Limited hardware resources and real-time environment lack authentication and integrity mechanisms, making the vehicle network vulnerable.
In present activities, the student shall develop a CAN Intrusion Detection System (IDS) based on Neural Network plausibility data to improve today’s authentication and integrity mechanism system without affecting hardware crypto accelerations resources.', ARRAY['Neural Networks']::text[], 'In collaboration with PUNCH Softronix', '2023-12-16', 1, ARRAY['L-14 - Legal Services Sciences','L-07 - Civil and Environmental Engineering']::text[]),
('Distributed Control of HVAC Systems for Emergency Demand Response', 442, 'marchetto.guido@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['sacco.alessio@tmtest.polito.it','Prof. Simone Silvestri - University Of Kentucky','Usa']::text[], ARRAY['modern power systems when a peak','modern power systems when a peak',' in ']::text[], 'Tesi all''estero', ARRAY['Dauin - Gr-03 - Computer Networks Group - Netgroup']::text[], 'Recent weather events in Texas and California have shown the vulnerability of modern power systems when a peak of demand appears as a consequence of extreme temperatures. Today, IoT-based smart thermostats are becoming pervasive, offering new opportunities to apply intelligent control during these events, and prevent large scale blackouts. In this thesis, we will study distributed control strategies to mitigate peak loads. These strategies are inspired by distributed network control protocols for flow and congestion control. Additionally, the student will be required to learn the software Energy Plus to perform realistic experiments.', ARRAY[]::text[], '', '2024-05-04', 1, ARRAY['L-30 - Physical Sciences and Technologies','L-26 - Agri-Food Sciences and Technologies']::text[]),
