('Design and Validation of a Safety-Critical Architecture for a Airborne System using MATLAB and Simulink', 452, 'sterpone.luca@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY['ELECTRICAL SYSTEMS','SAFETY CRITICAL SOFTWARE']::text[], 'RICERCA CON AZIENDA', ARRAY['Dauin - Aerospace And Safety Computing Lab']::text[], 'The main goal of the thesis is the design, modelling and validation of an innovative, safety-critical, internal communication system for airborne vehicle. 
Tipically, in airborn systems, the functional replication with comparison is used as main mitigation solution to guarantee the reliability of the computations. This strategy is used on several structural levels, from the main flight computing operations down to the peripheral management. In the thesis, the student will explore several fault mitigation solutions, in terms of physical and logical topology, transmission protocols and other parameters, keeping in mind the strict safety and performance requirements implied by such a system. The design and validation of the proposed solution will be performed through MATLAB and Simulink models.
The thesis has an high research orientation and it is performed in cooperation with an important industrial partner based in Turin.', ARRAY['Conoscenza elementare di Matlab']::text[], '', '2024-04-05', 1, ARRAY['L-38 - Zootechnical Sciences and Animal Production Technologies','L-24 - Psychological Sciences and Techniques','L-21 - Territorial, Urban, Landscape, and Environmental Planning']::text[]),
('Homographic squatting generation made possible', 193, 'mellia.marco@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['Idilio Drago
Rodolfo Viera']::text[], ARRAY['CYBERSECURITY','MACHINE LEARNING','ARTIFICIAL NEURAL NETWORKS','PHISHING']::text[], 'EXPERIMENTAL', ARRAY['Smartdata@Polito','Telecommunication Networks Group']::text[], 'Homographic attack is a well-known squatting technique uses the visual similarity between characters to lure users into phishing campaigns (e.g., word and vvord). In this thesis the student will investigate the use of multi-modal generative models to generate homographic attacks using visual feedback. The visual feedback, obtained with techniques employed in computer vision, will inform the models about the similarity between characters and their context in words to generate words that can increase the effectiveness of the attack. This approach has a huge potential when we consider the internationalized scenarios (URLs), in which words can include a mix of character sets from various alphabets, such as Cyrilic and Persian, as well as the possibility of using multiple font types and sizes when transmitting phishing messages. The student will design and evaluate machine learn models capable of generate such attacks based on the actual graphic similarity between generated candidate words and target words.', ARRAY['- Interest in cyber-security
