('Vehicle-to-everything & C-ITS technologies for smart parking spot finding', 99, 'patti.edoardo@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['Davide Tonella (D.Tonella@Reply.It)']::text[], ARRAY['BLOCKCHAIN','SMART VEHICLES']::text[], 'SPERIMENTALE', ARRAY['Dauin - Gr-06 - Electronic Design Automation - Eda','Electronic Design Automation - Eda','Energy Center Lab','Gr-06 - Electronic Design Automation - Eda','Ict4Ss - Ict For Smart Societies']::text[], 'The scope of the thesis is exploiting the capabilities of smart vehicles, and in particular of the Cooperative Intelligent Transport Systems (C-ITS) protocol (https://www.car-2-car.org/about-c-its), that provides a framework for structured and efficient message transmission both for vehicle-to-vehicle and vehicle-to-infrastructure applications. In particular, the aim is to develop an algorithm that, given the position of the vehicle, can find the closest free parking spot, and develop a system that can work even when no GPS signal is available, as is the case, for example, in underground parking lots.
 The candidate will be required to:
1.	Implement an algorithm to find the closest free parking spot given a reference location
2.	Study the interaction between smart parking and no-GPS navigation (via 5G and other wireless technologies)
3.	Create a scenario for end-to-end simulation that uses the hardware antennas for transmission and reception of messages
 The thesis will be supported by Concept Engineering Reply (https://www.reply.com/concept-reply), the company within the Reply Group specializing in digitizing and making the physical world smart through the development of IoT solutions applied to products, processes, and services. Concept Engineering relies on a group of experts in the fields of embedded systems (hardware and firmware), edge computing, IoT platforms, cloud computing, user channels, AI, ML, project management and PMO.
The target markets include automotive (and transportation in a broad sense), manufacturing, telco & media, insurance & finance, and medical. Additionally, an essential component of Concept Engineering is research and development, which aims to explore new technological frontiers to generate innovation.
Quality, innovation, flexibility, and enjoyment are the fundamental ingredients for making our projects successful and satisfying our clients.', ARRAY['Linux, programming languages, Good programming skills']::text[], '', '2024-10-24', 2, ARRAY['LM-30 - Master Degree in Energy and Nuclear Engineering','LM-22 - Master Degree in Chemical Engineering']::text[]),
('Self-Sovereign Identity and its Integration in an Energy Data Marketplace', 226, 'gatteschi.valentina@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['Alfredo Favenza']::text[], ARRAY['BLOCKCHAIN','DATA MARKETPLACES','SELF-SOVEREIGN IDENTITY']::text[], 'Tesi esterna in azienda', ARRAY['Dauin - Gr-09 - Graphics And Intelligent Systems - Grains']::text[], 'Self-Sovereign Identity is a new digital identity model that empowers individuals to control their identity without relying on centralized authorities. SSI enables the creation, management, and verification of digital identities that are self-owned, portable, and interoperable. In the context of an energy data marketplace, SSI can potentially enable secure and efficient sharing of energy data while giving individuals control over their data.
 This thesis aims to explore the concept of Self-Sovereign Identity (SSI) and its potential integration within an energy data marketplace. The purpose of the research is to analyze the algorithms used to enable the methodology of SSI, and investigate the implications of adopting SSI in an energy data marketplace. This research aims to contribute to the body of knowledge on the use of SSI in various applications and provide a practical demonstration of its implementation in an energy data marketplace.
 In particular, the research will begin with a comprehensive review of the literature on SSI and its algorithms and will examine its applicability to an energy data marketplace. The study will investigate the technical and social implications of SSI integration in the marketplace and identify potential benefits and limitations.
 The research will then proceed to identify the most suitable SSI algorithms for the energy data marketplace and investigate the feasibility of implementing them.
 The thesis will be developed in collaboration with LINKS Foundation.', ARRAY[]::text[], '', '2024-03-10', 1, ARRAY['L-08 - Computer Engineering','L-22 - Motor and Sports Activities Sciences','L-30 - Physical Sciences and Technologies']::text[]),
