('Using trending topic in Online Social Networks for recommendation systems', 45, 'trevisan.martino@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['vassio.luca@tmtest.polito.it','Greta Vallero (Det)']::text[], ARRAY['BIG DATA','DATA SCIENCE','MODELLAZIONE','RETI SOCIALI']::text[], 'DATA ANALYSIS', ARRAY['Smartdata@Polito','Telecommunication Networks Group']::text[], 'The candidate will build on top of previous work from the research group and will design and engineer a real-time analyzer of social networks (Facebook and Instagram) to extract trending topics and provide these to a recommendation system. The student will use large quantities of data from social networks. The data will be organized and analyzed using big data techniques (such as Pyspark). Then, the student will improve a current methodology to dynamically extract trending topics and the words/sentences that characterize them. These will be used to search within a catalogue of items for recommender systems. The student will also analyze the performance evaluation of the whole engineered system. Possibly, a dynamic web interface will be published to provide results to the public.', ARRAY['Data analysis, python programing, preferentially big data (pyspark), machine learning, graphs']::text[], 'Contact luca.vassio@tmtest.polito.it', '2024-04-20', 1, ARRAY['L-05 - Philosophy']::text[]),
('Learning technology for students'' assessment', 190, 'sanna.andrea@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['Manuri Federico']::text[], ARRAY['CORREZIONE AUTOMATICA DI ESAMI DI RENDERING']::text[], 'RICERCA', ARRAY['Dauin - Gr-09 - Graphics And Intelligent Systems - Grains']::text[], 'Il termine "learning technology" descrive l''uso di strumenti tecnologici, comunicativi ed informativi per migliorare l''apprendimento, l''insegnamento e la valutazione. La recente pandemia ha portato ad un massiccio uso di queste tecnologie per far fronte ai problemi logistici ed organizzativi legati ai periodi di quarantena e lock down ma non solo. Questo ha messo in luce limitazioni e problematiche dei sistemi esistenti ma anche il ruolo chiave che queste tecnologie possono avere per migliorare il processo di apprendimento.
 Questa tesi si prefigge la creazione di uno strumento di valutazione per studenti iscritti al corso di "Rendering per il design" del corso di studi in "Design e comunicazione visiva". Lo strumento, nella forma di un portale web accessibile dagli studenti, dovrà fornire un sistema di autovalutazione dei render 3D realizzati dagli studenti, tramite confronto con un riferimento dato, basandosi sulle più recenti tecniche di computer vision ed intelligenza artificiale.', ARRAY['Sono consigliate conoscenze di intelligenza artificiale']::text[], '', '2024-09-13', 2, ARRAY['LM-29 - Master Degree in Electronic Engineering','LM-08 - Master Degree in Industrial Biotechnology']::text[]),
('LPV modelling and control of wave energy conversion systems', 470, 'ezequielfaedo.nicolas@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['Dr. Demián Garcia-Violini (Universidad Nacional De Quilmes','Argentina)']::text[], ARRAY['CONTROL SYSTEMS','DATA ANALYSIS','MODELLING','SYSTEM DYNAMICS','SYSTEM IDENTIFICATION','WAVE ENERGY - HYDRODYNAMICS - NUMERICAL MODELLING']::text[], 'MASTER THESIS', ARRAY['More Lab _ Http://Www.Morenergylab.Polito.It']::text[], 'Wave energy conversion devices, commonly referred to as wave energy converters (WECs), need to be controlled in
order to maximise the energy extraction from the ocean wave resource, hence directly lowering the associated levelised
cost of energy.
 Control for WEC systems departs from standard regulation/tracking objectives, commonly employed in control engineering:
The objective is that of maximising energy extraction, and not that of following/tracking a given set-point/reference.
As such, the vast majority of the WEC control techniques employ lie within the field of optimal control theory, where
an associated optimal control problem (OCP) is solved in real-time to compute the corresponding control action. OCPs
are virtually always model-based: That is, a dynamical model of the WEC system is required in order to predict future
motion, enforce constraints, and maximise the energy objective. These models need to be parsimonious in terms of
both computational and analytical complexity, in order to facilitate real-time calculations, i.e. to be implementable.
In the pathway towards building these control-oriented models, a number of potentially limiting standing assumptions
are often adopted. These modelling hypotheses, which aim at simplifying the dynamical description of the WEC system,
inherently introduce a large degree of uncertainty in the control design problem. This project will explore the use of
linear parameter varying (LPV) representations for WEC systems in order to achieve robust performance for controllers
aiming at maximising energy extraction from the wave resource. LPV systems feature a closed-form representation of a
system in terms of a set of scheduling parameters, offering the possibility of incorporating dynamical behaviour which
is often neglected in purely linear models.

