('Exploration and Implementation of a PoC for Digital Battery Passport (DBP) System for Electric Vehicle Batteries (Storm Reply)', 491, 'bazzanella.danilo@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['Presso Storm Reply']::text[], ARRAY['BLOCKCHAIN','ELECTRIC VEHICLE']::text[], 'TESI IN AZIENDA', ARRAY['Crittografia E Teoria Dei Numeri']::text[], 'This thesis project offers a unique opportunity to delve into the innovative world of the electric vehicle (EV) industry, focusing specifically on the implementation of a PoC for Digital Battery Passport (DBP) system. This system, which leverages the power of Blockchain technology and AWS services, aims to provide a unified, transparent and secure method of tracking an EV battery''s life cycle. You will be part of an initiative that could transform not just the future of mobility, but also contribute significantly to environmental sustainability. The objective is to design and develop an Electric Vehicle Battery passport leveraging the AWS Managed Blockchain service and evaluate KPIs for comparison with Blockchain solution of third parties.
 What you will learn:
You will have the opportunity to deep dive into Blockchain technology and its potential applications in different sectors, with a specific focus on the electric vehicle industry.
 What you will build:
A simulated data source using an AWS SQS queue to mimic real-time data from an actual EV battery.
A system using AWS services to process and manage the data received from the simulated data source.
Integration of the DBP system with Amazon Managed Blockchain, enabling secure and verifiable data transactions.
A simple-interface that allows stakeholders (e.g., vehicle owners, service centers, regulatory authorities) to interact with the DBP system.
Automation scripts using Terraform to manage the infrastructure of the system.', ARRAY[]::text[], '', '2024-08-18', 2, ARRAY['LM-31 - Master Degree in Management Engineering']::text[]),
('Vehicles & blockchain: EVs as actuators for power grid load optimization', 99, 'patti.edoardo@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['Davide Tonella (D.Tonella@Reply.It)']::text[], ARRAY['BLOCKCHAIN','ELECTRIC VEHICLE','SMART GRID','SMART VEHICLES']::text[], 'SPERIMENTALE', ARRAY['Dauin - Gr-06 - Electronic Design Automation - Eda','Electronic Design Automation - Eda','Energy Center Lab','Gr-06 - Electronic Design Automation - Eda','Ict4Ss - Ict For Smart Societies']::text[], 'The scope of the thesis is exploring the possibilities that the blockchain and tokenization technologies could bring to the world of smart grid and electric vehicles applications. In a scenario where EVs can exchange tokens for energy on the blockchain, the vehicles could gather significant insight on the state of the power grid itself.
The idea is to exploit this opportunity to study charging patterns and behaviors to promote a more sustainable load balancing on the grid.
 The candidate will be required to:
1.	Design and develop a framework that allows the power grid to share insight on its load state
2.	Study an optimization strategy for energy load balancing
3.	Cooperate with backend and blockchain domains experts, to ensure the flexibility, safety and reliability of the proposed solution
 The thesis will be supported by Concept Engineering Reply (https://www.reply.com/concept-reply), the company within the Reply Group specializing in digitizing and making the physical world smart through the development of IoT solutions applied to products, processes, and services. Concept Engineering relies on a group of experts in the fields of embedded systems (hardware and firmware), edge computing, IoT platforms, cloud computing, user channels, AI, ML, project management and PMO.
The target markets include automotive (and transportation in a broad sense), manufacturing, telco & media, insurance & finance, and medical. Additionally, an essential component of Concept Engineering is research and development, which aims to explore new technological frontiers to generate innovation.
Quality, innovation, flexibility, and enjoyment are the fundamental ingredients for making our projects successful and satisfying our clients.', ARRAY['C++, blockchain, MQTT or other communication protocol']::text[], '', '2024-10-24', 1, ARRAY['L-21 - Territorial, Urban, Landscape, and Environmental Planning']::text[]),
('Progettazione di sistemi di gestione di batterie (BMS) per veicoli elettrici', 329, 'sansoe.claudio@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['Ing. Maurizio Tranchero']::text[], ARRAY['BATTERY MANAGEMENT SYSTEM','VEICOLI ELETTRICI ED IBRIDI']::text[], 'PROGETTUALE E SPERIMENTALE', ARRAY['LM-32 group 1','LM-08 group 1','LM-25 group 2']::text[], 'Per gestire al meglio la carica e la scarica delle batterie dei veicoli elettrici, all’interno di esse sono presenti delle centraline specifiche di controllo e gestione chiamate battery management system (BMS). I BMS hanno come scopo monitorare lo stato di carica delle batterie, la temperatura delle varie celle, equalizzare lo stato carica delle celle, ed interagire con il resto del veicolo.
L’obiettivo di questa tesi è di realizzare una centralina BMS per una applicazione di mobilità elettrica. Una volta scelta l’architettura, i chip di monitoraggio, lo studente completerà la progettazione di tutta la centralina (microcontrollore, interfacce di comunicazione, condizionamento dei segnali). Una volta progettato lo schema elettrico, si procederà a progettare il circuito stampato. Una volta realizzati i prototipi, lo studente dovrà verificarne il funzionamento in laboratorio e, se possibile, su veicolo.', ARRAY['Elettronica analogica e di potenza, simulazione con SPICE, lingua inglese']::text[], '50 % in azienda e 50 % in università', '2024-07-14', 2, ARRAY['LM-32 - Master Degree in Computer Engineering','LM-08 - Master Degree in Industrial Biotechnology','LM-25 - Master Degree in Automation Engineering']::text[]),
('Extending the Open-source TVM Compiler to Deploy Deep Neural Networks on the GreenWaves'' GAP9 Platform', 331, 'jahierpagliari.daniele@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['Marco Fariselli (Greenwaves Technologies)
Alessio Burrello (Politecnico Di Torino)']::text[], ARRAY['ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE','C','COMPILERS','CONVOLUTIONAL NEURAL NETWORKS','DEEP LEARNING','DEEP NEURAL NETWORKS','EMBEDDED SYSTEMS','ENERGY EFFICIENCY','FIRMWARE','LOW POWER','MICROCONTROLLERS','MULTI-CORE','PARALLEL COMPUTING','SOFTWARE','SOFTWARE ACCELERATION','TRANSFORMERS','TVM']::text[], 'EXPERIMENTAL, SOFTWARE DEVELOPMENT', ARRAY['Dauin - Gr-06 - Electronic Design Automation - Eda','Electronic Design Automation - Eda','Gr-06 - Electronic Design Automation - Eda']::text[], 'Apache TVM is an open-source compiler for deep learning, which automates the conversion of high-level Python models (e.g. in Tensorflow or Pytorch) to optimzied code that runs on GPUs, CPUs, or accelerators. Recently uTVM has also brought support for embedded systems and low-power microcontrollers. In particular, many devices based on ARM microcontrollers are currently supported and achieve performances equal to the state of the art deep learning libraries, but with a code developed automatically by uTVM, thus reducing the programmer''s effort.
 The aim of this thesis is to extend TVM support to a multi-core and heterogeneous platforms based on RISC-V microcontrollers.
 The platform is GreenWaves'' GAP9, which currently (Dec. 2022) achieves a record energy efficiency on the most popular set of benchmarks for efficient Deep Learning inference: https://greenwaves-technologies.com/lowest-energy-consumption-on-all-mlperf-tiny-v1-0-benchmarks/
 The goal of this thesis is the integration between TVM and NN-tool, a proprietary tool for deployment on GAP9. The outcome of the thesis should be a tool that exploits the TVM framework to read the deep neural network high-level model, parses it, and uses NN-tool to produce code specific for GAP9. The goal is to produce a general tool that match the performance of existing, platform-specific tools.
 Interested candidates must send an email to daniele.jahier@tmtest.polito.it attaching their CV and exams'' transcript with scores.', ARRAY['Required skills include C and python programming. Further, a basic knowledge of computer architectures and embedded systems is necessary. Desired (but not required) skills include some familiarity with basic machine/deep learning concepts and corresponding models.']::text[], 'Thesis in collaboration with the company GreenWaves technologies, and the research group of Prof. Luca Benini at the University of Bologna and ETH Zurich, and Greenwaves Technologies.', '2023-12-14', 1, ARRAY['L-17 - Architectural Sciences','L-32 - Environmental and Nature Sciences and Technologies','L-34 - Geological Sciences']::text[]),
('Definition of a procedure for testing PV-system arc-fault detectors according to the international standard IEC 63027', 490, 'carullo.alessio@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['vallan.alberto@tmtest.polito.it','Marco Piva','Mario Comboni (Tuv Rheinland)']::text[], ARRAY['innescare',' di ']::text[], 'Tesi esterna in azienda', ARRAY['Low Frequency Measurement Group']::text[], 'Uno dei maggiori rischi per i sistemi FotoVoltaici (FV) deriva dagli archi in serie, pertanto l''obiettivo del Comitato Elettrico Internazionale (IEC) consiste nel fornire i requisiti per le apparecchiature di protezione contro i guasti da arco voltaico, in modo da ridurre il rischio di innescare un incendio. Molti dispositivi rilevano gli archi analizzando e confrontando l''emissione del segnale ad alta frequenza dell''arco; lo scopo di questi dispositivi è garantire che la maggior parte degli archi in serie in un sistema fotovoltaico sia rilevata.
La norma internazionale IEC 63027 definisce un percorso di certificazione dei rilevatori di guasti da arco elettrico dei sistemi fotovoltaici e un insieme di configurazioni di prova adatte alle varie topologie di sistema previste (la bozza finale della norma ha iniziato a circolare a gennaio 2023).
L''obiettivo della tesi è quello di sviluppare e validare la procedura di prova dei dispositivi di protezione da arco elettrico secondo le indicazioni della norma IEC 63027.
La soluzione deve includere anche la valutazione dell''incertezza e della ripetibilità del metodo di prova e la taratura delle apparecchiature di prova.', ARRAY['Electrical and electronic circuits, measurement principles']::text[], 'The thesis shall be carried at TUV Rheinland Italia laboratories, which are located in Pogliano Milanese (MI).
A typical duration of 6 months is foreseen for this thesis activity.', '2024-02-03', 2, ARRAY['LM-18 - Master Degree in Computer Science']::text[]),
('Sviluppo di un Serious Game basato su Escape Room per l''Apprendimento della Programmazione Orientata agli Oggetti', 133, 'coppola.riccardo@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY['GAMIFICATION','TESTING']::text[], 'Tesi di Laurea', ARRAY['Dauin - Gr-16 - Software Engineering Group - Softeng']::text[], 'Descrizione: La programmazione orientata agli oggetti (OOP) è un concetto fondamentale nell''informatica, ma può essere complessa da apprendere per gli studenti principianti. La comprensione dei concetti fondamentali, richiede spesso un approccio interattivo e coinvolgente per consolidare il loro apprendimento. In risposta a questa esigenza, l''uso di serious games, come escape room e i puzzle game, è emerso come una strategia pedagogica promettente per migliorare l''apprendimento degli studenti nei corsi di programmazione ad oggetti.
 L''obiettivo principale di questa tesi è sviluppare un serious game innovativo, basato su un''ambientazione narrativa coinvolgente e un tema ben definito, per favorire l''apprendimento efficace della programmazione orientata agli oggetti. Inoltre, questa ricerca mira a integrare il serious game nell''ambiente di insegnamento del corso di programmazione ad oggetti, valutandone l''impatto sull''apprendimento degli studenti e raccogliendo feedback per valutare l''efficacia  e l''UX del gioco come strumento didattico.', ARRAY['Sviluppo in Java o altri linguaggi OOP, rudimenti di Software Testing']::text[], '', '2024-10-13', 1, ARRAY['L-02 - Biotechnology','L-33 - Economic Sciences']::text[]),
('AR for conveying defects information to production line operators with collaborative robot assistance', 91, 'lamberti.fabrizio@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY['INDUSTRIA 5.0','INTERFACCE UOMO-MACCHINA','REALTÀ AUMENTATA','ROBOTICA COLLABORATIVA']::text[], 'TESI IN COLLAB. CON AZIENDA', ARRAY['Gr-09 - Graphics And Intelligent Systems - Grains']::text[], 'In modern production processes, the efficient detection and management of defects are critical for ensuring high-quality output and optimizing manufacturing operations. The advent of automation and advanced computer vision techniques has enabled the automatic detection of defects in real-time. However, conveying this vital information to production line operators in a clear, intuitive, and timely manner remains a challenge. This thesis proposal aims to investigate the application of Augmented Reality (AR) technology, enhanced by Collaborative Robot (Cobot) assistance, as a means of conveying automatically detected defects information to production line operators. The research will involve the integration of the output from computer vision algorithms and defect detection methodologies within a production line. Cobots will be instrumental in assisting operators during the tasks of defect detection and correction. By utilizing AR technology, the proposed investigation seeks to overlay defect-related information, such as visual cues, guidance, and instructions, directly onto the physical production environment in real-time, with the Cobot playing a pivotal role in enhancing the operator''s capabilities and accuracy during defect management tasks. This approach aims to enhance operators'' situational awareness, enable rapid decision-making, and facilitate timely defect resolution. The research collaboration will actively engage industry partners, ensuring the practicality and relevance of the findings. Moreover, the project will be in alignment with the overarching objectives of the MANAGE 5.0 project, with support from the Ministry of Enterprises and Made in Italy (MISE) and the National Recovery and Resilience Plan (PNRR).

