('Impact of measurement uncertainty on the performance of machine learning models for the safeguards verification of spent fuel assemblies', 172, 'testoni.raffaella@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['Dr. Riccardo Rossa (Sck-Cen)','Dr. Alessandro Borella (Sck-Cen)']::text[], ARRAY[' the ','Previous work focused on']::text[], 'Tesi di Laurea', ARRAY['L-43 group 1','L-06 group 2']::text[], 'Previous work focused on the development of machine learning models for the detection and localization of replaced pins. Current models treat the measurement results only and do not take into account the statistical measurement uncertainty in their analysis.', ARRAY[]::text[], '', '2024-01-25', 1, ARRAY['L-43 - Technologies for Cultural Heritage Conservation and Restoration','L-06 - Geography']::text[]),
('Mimicking visual memory in stimuli-responsive material', 205, 'amati.nicola@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['frascella.francesca@tmtest.polito.it','Angelo Angelini - Inrim']::text[], ARRAY['materiali responsivi a stimoli luminosi che verranno caratterizzati e utilizzati nel campo dell''intelligenza artificiale','materiali responsivi a stimoli luminosi che verranno caratterizzati e utilizzati nel campo dell''intelligenza artificiale',' di ']::text[], 'SPERIMENTALE', ARRAY['Aa - Materials And Processes For Micro And Nano Technologies']::text[], 'Sviluppo di materiali responsivi a stimoli luminosi che verranno caratterizzati e utilizzati nel campo dell''intelligenza artificiale', ARRAY[]::text[], '', '2024-09-29', 2, ARRAY['LM-31 - Master Degree in Management Engineering']::text[]),
('Computatational Analysis of the Interaction between fibrinogen and COVID-19 spike protein', 302, 'adamtuszynski.jacek@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['Alessandro Santin','Yale University','Usa
Maral Aminpour','University Of Alberta','Canada']::text[], ARRAY['COVID-19','DOCKING','FIBRINOGEN','HOMOLOGY MODELLING','IVERMECTIN','SPIKE PROTEIN']::text[], 'COMPUTATIONAL', ARRAY['28- Biomedica']::text[], 'A recent publication indicated that Spike may bind directly to fibrinogen resulting in an induction of structurally abnormal blood clots with heightened proinflammatory activity. This is intriguing since it may provide an additional explanation for the development of micro-clotting in both acute Covid, Long Covid and in particular fully vaccinated individuals after received multiple shots using a pathogenic mechanism different from direct endothelial damage. We also now know that persistent production of Spike has now been demonstrated in human plasma and tissue cells for weeks during the acute infection and now for months/years in Long Covid. Importantly, the fibrotic (ie, fibrin Amyloid) clots causing thousands of deaths these days are notorious for being difficult to treat since they are highly resistant to fibrinolysis.  Importantly, IVM may also have a beneficial effect both in acute infection, long covid as well as vaccinated patients since binding to the Spike protein may also potentially interfere with the binding to fibrinogen blocking/decreasing micro-clotting formation in individuals chronically producing spike protein. The crystal structure of spike is knowns. Fibrinogen structure is known for bovine and chicken but not human. However, we can create a human fibrinogen structure computationally using homology modeling. This would be the first step in the project. The second would be to dock spike protein to fibrinogen and evaluate the binding mode and strength of their interaction. Finally, using blind docking we will obtain the most probably interaction sites of ivermectin on fibrinogen. This will enable us to assess the correctness of the above hypothesis.', ARRAY['computational modeling of proteins and ligands, docking, homology modeling and molecular dynamics']::text[], 'This project will be performed in collaboration with researchers in Canada and the US. The student may perform the computational work in Italy or in Canada.', '2024-03-01', 2, ARRAY['LM-04 - Master Degree in Architectural and Building Engineering-Architecture','LM-13 - Master Degree in Pharmacy and Industrial Pharmacy','LM-20 - Master Degree in Aerospace and Astronautical Engineering']::text[]),
('progettazione e sintesi di catalizzatori nanostrutturati per la (foto)degradazione di inquinanti emergenti ', 510, 'esposito.serena@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['tammaro.olimpia@tmtest.polito.it']::text[], ARRAY['FOTOCATALISI','INQUINANTI','NANOMATERIALI INGEGNERIZZATI']::text[], 'Tesi di Laurea', ARRAY['Aa - Surf-Chem']::text[], 'strategie di sintesi per la preparazione di materiali attivi per la fotodegradazione di inquinanti emergenti.', ARRAY[]::text[], '', '2024-01-24', 2, ARRAY['LM-05 - Master Degree in Archival Studies and Library Science','LM-02 - Master Degree in Archaeology','LM-01 - Master Degree in Cultural Anthropology and Ethnology']::text[]),
('AI-based radiomics for glioma diagnosis', 432, 'dicataldo.santa@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['Francesco.Ponzio@tmtest.polito.it']::text[], ARRAY['ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE','MACHINE LEARNING','ARTIFICIAL NEURAL NETWORKS','MEDICAL IMAGING']::text[], 'Tesi di Laurea', ARRAY['Dauin - Gr-06 - Electronic Design Automation - Eda']::text[], 'The early and accurate diagnosis of post-treatment tumor progression (TP) in high-grade gliomas (HGGs) is crucial to improve overall survival (OS) as it can drive optimal therapy. However, new enhanced lesions often appear on MRI in the treatment area which can be due to pseudoprogression (PsP) and treatment-related changes (TRCs). 
The aim of the thesis is to develop a novel deep learning-based radiomics tool for the classification of TP, PsP and TRCs leveraging MRI sequences.
The thesis activity, done in strict collaboration with the University of Brescia, will require the following steps:
Literature analysis, looking for the state-of-the-art systems currently available.
Delineation of a preliminary dataset on-line available.
Design of a deep learning-based architecture for the above-mentioned classification task
Optional. Testing/fine-tuning plus testing on a novel cohort of patients, gathered in the mean-while within the collaboration of several hospitals.', ARRAY['Good programming skills (Python). Biomedical background and prior knowledge of Machine Learning/Deep Learning design frameworks is a plus.']::text[], '', '2024-07-28', 1, ARRAY['L-14 - Legal Services Sciences']::text[]),
('Sviluppo di una Wireless Body Area Network (WBAN) per l''analisi del movimento', 444, 'demarchi.danilo@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['Fabio Rossi (Fabio.Rossi@tmtest.polito.it)','Andrea Mongardi (Andrea.Mongardi@tmtest.polito.it)']::text[], ARRAY['ANALISI DEL MOVIMENTO','BLUETOOTH LOW ENERGY','PROTOCOLLI DI COMUNICAZIONE','WIRELESS BODY AREA NETWORK (WBAN)']::text[], 'SPERIMENTALE', ARRAY['Mines (Micro&Nano Electronic Systems)']::text[], 'Nell''epoca odierna di innovazione tecnologica, il settore riabilitativo e quello sportivo si stanno evolvendo integrando strumenti che permettono al corpo umano di interfacciarsi con l''elettronica per fornire dati preziosi. In particolare, l''analisi del movimento tramite sensori inerziali (IMU) e dispositivi per l''acquisizione del segnale elettromiografico di superficie (sEMG) copre un ruolo chiave in questi due settori. Infatti, il gruppo di ricerca MiNES negli ultimi anni ha sviluppato dispositivi a basso consumo per il monitoraggio dell''attività muscolare, e recentemente ha iniziato a integrarne le funzionalità con sensori inerziali. Lo scopo di questo lavoro di tesi è la realizzazione di un protocollo di comunicazione wireless basato su Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE) al fine di ottenere una Wireless Body Area Network (WBAN) che permetta un utilizzo sinergico dei dispositivi sviluppati dal gruppo di ricerca. Fra i problemi da affrontare rientreranno la definizione della topologia della rete, la sincronizzazione dei dispositivi coinvolti, l''alternanza dei ruoli di master e slave, e la limitazione della quantità di dati utili trasmessi dalla rete.', ARRAY['Programmazione in C, Sviluppo di firmware (MCU)']::text[], '', '2023-11-21', 2, ARRAY['LM-18 - Master Degree in Computer Science','LM-22 - Master Degree in Chemical Engineering','LM-32 - Master Degree in Computer Engineering']::text[]),
('Studi di impatto ambientale per sistemi energetici', 172, 'testoni.raffaella@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['Mauro Montruccio (Rams&E)']::text[], ARRAY[' di ',' con ','impatto ambientale']::text[], 'Tesi di Laurea', ARRAY['LM-08 group 1','LM-14 group 1']::text[], 'Sviluppo di studi di impatto ambientale con riferimento ad impianti energetici. Tesi dal risvolto professionale, possibilità di tirocinio presso aziende del settore energetico.', ARRAY[]::text[], '', '2024-03-17', 2, ARRAY['LM-08 - Master Degree in Industrial Biotechnology','LM-14 - Master Degree in Modern Philology']::text[]),
('Fast Secure Boot for Safety-critical Automotive applications', 475, 'dicarlo.stefano@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['savino.alessandro@tmtest.polito.it','Obert Franco']::text[], ARRAY['AUTHENTICATION','AUTOMOTIVE','IDENTITY MANAGEMENT','SECURE BOOT','SECURITY']::text[], 'APPLICATIVA, RICERCA APPLICATA, RICERCA SPERIMENTALE, SVILUPPO HARDWARE', ARRAY['Dauin - Gr-24 - Smilies - Resilient Computer Architectures And Life Sci']::text[], 'The Secure Boot ensures that the authenticated program runs on the system. It is crucial verifying the execution code integrity to guarantee that no malicious software runs. This dominant technique has to pay a high cost in terms of time and processing power. Especially the computational time is critical in automotive safety-critical controllers. The reason is driven by the real-time requirements that give a limited time to complete the integrity check on the on-chip system’s memory. On one side, functional safety systems restrict security checks. On the other hand, the system shall guarantee high-security levels for its runs. The cryptography primitives are the main contributor that enlarge the bootstrap time even if hardware accelerators are in use. The student shall develop a Fast Secure Boot (FSB) that won’t be based on cryptography using advanced techniques, such as High performers Counter (HPC) and Machine Learning (ML), continuing to guarantee the same level of security reached by today’s standard Secure Boots.', ARRAY[]::text[], 'In collaboration with PUNCH Softronix', '2023-11-28', 1, ARRAY['L-21 - Territorial, Urban, Landscape, and Environmental Planning','L-26 - Agri-Food Sciences and Technologies','L-23 - Construction Sciences and Techniques']::text[]),
('Utilizzo di tecniche di computer vision per analisi di safe separation', 508, 'battipede.manuela@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY['Tesi da svolgere presso Leonardo Elicotteri']::text[], 'Tesi esterna in azienda', ARRAY['15-Modellazione','Simulazione E Controllo Di Velivoli']::text[], 'Tesi da svolgere presso Leonardo Elicotteri', ARRAY[]::text[], '', '2024-06-19', 1, ARRAY['L-17 - Architectural Sciences','L-05 - Philosophy','L-14 - Legal Services Sciences']::text[]),
('Climate models: from simple thermodynamics to atmosphere-ocean circulation dynamics', 309, 'novara.carlo@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['Prof. Enrico Canuto']::text[], ARRAY['CLIMATE CHANGE MITIGATION','CLIMATE DATA ANALYSIS','CO2 DYNAMICS','MODEL IDENTIFICATION','SIMULATION']::text[], 'Descrizione', ARRAY['Automatica Group - Det']::text[], 'No description available', ARRAY['Basic and advanced notions about dynamic systems','Matlab/Simulink programming.']::text[], 'If you are interested, send your CV (including the attended courses and exam grades) to carlo.novara@tmtest.polito.it', '2023-12-15', 1, ARRAY['L-40 - Sociology','L-05 - Philosophy']::text[]),
('Network games, equilibrium learning and intervention', 224, 'dallasta.luca@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY['INCENTIVI','RETI SOCIALI','SISTEMI COMPLESSI','TEORIA DEI GIOCHI']::text[], 'Tesi di Laurea', ARRAY['Aa - Statistical Physics And Interdisciplinary Applications']::text[], 'Network games are stylized strategic problems in which individual utilities are affected by local externalities on a given interaction network. Depending on the level of knowledge agents have on the local/global structure of the network, different solution concepts have been proposed to describe collective rational behavior. For instance, self-confirming equilibria are generalizations of Nash equilibria in which a form of consistency between subjective utility functions and individual beliefs based on repeated observations is assumed. Such equilibria play an important role in the context of game-theoretic learning processes.  The thesis work is focused on the development of statistical physics methods to study the properties of self-confirming equilibria on networks, both from a static and dynamic point of view, and tackle the problem of optimal incentive allocation in network games.', ARRAY['Knowledge of fundamental concepts and methods in game theory, dynamical systems, and graph theory. Good programming skills (e.g. Python/Julia/C++).']::text[], '', '2024-02-02', 2, ARRAY['LM-03 - Master Degree in Landscape Architecture','LM-28 - Master Degree in Electrical Engineering','LM-20 - Master Degree in Aerospace and Astronautical Engineering']::text[]),
