('Modeling the EKG and blood pressure time series of patients exposed to an external source of electromagnetic waves', 302, 'adamtuszynski.jacek@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['Dr. Frederico Costa','Sirio-Libanes Hospital','Sao Paolo','Brazil']::text[], ARRAY['BLOOD PRESSURE','CHAOTIC DYNAMICS','HEART RATE VARIABILITY','NONLINEAR DIFFERENTIAL EQUATIONS','PHASE PLOTS','RADIO FREQUENCY ELECTROMAGNETIC WAVES','VAN DER POL EQUATION','WINDKESSEL EQUATION']::text[], 'COMPUTATIONAL', ARRAY['28- Biomedica']::text[], 'In this project, the student will analyze real patient data obtained in the Sirio-Libanes Hospital when HCC patients were exposed to a diagnostic and therapeutic device that generates radio-frequency waves of low intensity and low-frequency amplitude modulation. EKG data sets for various amplitude modulation frequencies will be analyzed for heart rate variability and simulated using the modified van der Pol equation. Similarly, blood pressure time series for the same exposures will be analyzed and simulated using the Windkessel equation. Finally, a correlation analysis between the two datasets will be performed in order to establish the physiological effects of the electromagnetic waves on the human body via hemodynamics.', ARRAY['an ability to use excel spreadsheet and program in matlab will be required']::text[], '', '2024-09-09', 2, ARRAY['LM-12 - Master Degree in Design','LM-09 - Master Degree in Medical, Veterinary, and Pharmaceutical Biotechnology']::text[]),
('VIRTUAL PRODUCTION WITH ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE FOR MOTION CAPTURE IN BROADCAST: BENEFITS, LIMITATIONS, AND PRODUCTION IMPLICATIONS', 23, 'bottino.andrea@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['mazali.tatiana@tmtest.polito.it']::text[], ARRAY['VIRTUAL PRODUCTION','MOTION CAPTURE','AI','INTERNSHIP']::text[], 'Tesi esterna in azienda', ARRAY['L-15 group 1']::text[], 'Virtual production is a cutting-edge technology that combines real-time visualization with pre-visualization in the film and television industry. Through the use of virtual reality and artificial intelligence, virtual production enables more efficient and creative ways of authoring and capturing media content. The goal of this thesis is to investigate the potential of virtual production and artificial intelligence, with special focus on motion capture techniques, in the field of broadcast production. Through a literature review, case studies, and interviews with industry professionals, the benefits and limitations of using artificial intelligence for motion capture in virtual production will be explored, as well as impacts on the production value chain (costs, workflow, human resources, and skills to name a few). Among the expected outcomes of this research is a better understanding of how virtual production and AI can improve the production process, increase the accuracy and realism of motion capture, and reduce production costs while maintaining or even improving the quality of the final product.
 During the internship, the student will work with qualified staff both in the Studio TV production center in Turin and in the Rai Research & Innovation Center offices.
 Possible thesis topics
 3D Content creation for broadcast virtual studio
 Markerless mocap vs marker mocap
 Integration of real-time MC systems with unreal engine
 • Analysis of the Production value chain (costs, workflow, skills…)
 Type of Thesis Experimental – Possibility of Internship
 Required skills Basic skills in the field of 3D graphics, software development and game engine programming.
 Thesis available for multiple students

