(' Adaptive control with applications to quadcopter UAVs ', 261, 'capello.elisa@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['Thesis In Collaboration With Prof. L''Afflitto','Grado Department Of Industrial And Systems Engineering At Virginia Tech']::text[], ARRAY[' This topic involves coding novel control algorithms',' unsteady payloads']::text[], 'Tesi di Laurea', ARRAY['08- Dinamica','Controllo E Simulazione Del Volo']::text[], 'Adaptive control with applications to quadcopter UAVs transporting large, unknown, unsteady payloads. This topic involves coding novel control algorithms in C++ and testing those on actual quadcopter UAVs and/or high-fidelity simulators based on PyChrono', ARRAY['Matlab/Simulink, C/C++']::text[], '', '2024-06-15', 1, ARRAY['L-18 - Economics and Business Management Sciences','L-07 - Civil and Environmental Engineering','L-35 - Mathematical Sciences']::text[]),
('Produzione e applicazione dei nuovi magneti permanenti, con RE e RE-free', 516, 'actisgrande.marco@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['ferraris.luca@tmtest.polito.it','poskovic.emir@tmtest.polito.it','tenconi.alberto@tmtest.polito.it','Fausto Franchini Fausto.Franchini@tmtest.polito.it']::text[], ARRAY['CARATTERIZZAZIONE MAGNETICA','MACCHINE ELETTRICHE','MAGNETI PERMANENTI','MAGNETIC MATERIALS','PROCESSI INNOVATIVI','SVILUPPO PRODOTTO']::text[], 'PROGETTAZIONE, SPERIMENTALE, SPERIMENTALE - PROGETTAZIONE, SPERIMENTALE IN LABORATORIO', ARRAY['Peemd']::text[], 'Riciclaggio NdFeB, materiali magnetici duri, test/banco di prova, sviluppo processo, caratterizzazione magnetica, LabView, acquisizione ed elaborazione dati, prototipazione e applicazione in macchine elettriche o sensoristica.', ARRAY[]::text[], '', '2023-12-21', 1, ARRAY['L-04 - Industrial Design']::text[]),
('Algorithm design for VNF migration in 5G edge clouds', 10, 'fabianachiasserini.carla@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['giaccone.paolo@tmtest.polito.it']::text[], ARRAY['DOCKER','EDGE COMPUTING']::text[], 'SIMULATION', ARRAY['Telecommunication Networks Group']::text[], 'The adoption of Virtual Function Virtualization (VNF) in 5G networks enables an unprecedented level of flexibility in providing new network services, but this comes at the cost of orchestrating carefully the required resources (cpu, memory, storage, network).
 The aim of the thesis is to devise new algorithms to optimize the migration of network functions to enable the users'' mobility in a 5G network. The work will consider specifically the state-of-the-art scenario in which Docker containers implement the network function.', ARRAY['Very strong programming skills. Cloud computing. Networking. Simulation.']::text[], '', '2023-12-12', 2, ARRAY['LM-08 - Master Degree in Industrial Biotechnology','LM-04 - Master Degree in Architectural and Building Engineering-Architecture']::text[]),
('Field (SAR) and temperature focusing in microwave cancer hyperthermia', 311, 'vecchi.giuseppe@tmtest.polito.it', ARRAY['Rossella Gaffoglio','Giorgio Giordanengo','Links Foundation']::text[], ARRAY['HYPERTHERMIA FOR CANCER TREATMENT','NUMERICAL SIMUL']::text[], 'MASTER THESIS', ARRAY['Applied Electromagnetics']::text[], 'Microwave  hyperthermia is a medical therapy currently employed in the clinic for cancer treatment, and whose associated research is translational. In it, tumor cells are selectively exposed to a supra-physiological temperature (42/43 °C) using proper antenna systems [1]. For internal tumors, this is currently achieved by means of an array of antennas equipped with a proper cooling system (the water bolus) to avoid overheating of the skin [2]. Since the effectiveness of a hyperthermia treatment is strictly dependent on the quality of the heating process, a treatment planning is fundamental to optimally set the amplitudes and phases of the applied signals. For this reason, different optimization techniques aimed at maximizing the specific absorption rate (SAR) or, directly, the temperature in the target region have been implemented, and much research is still devoted to make these techniques more effective, faster, and suitable for real-time applications. 
This thesis aims at optimizing the microwave heating of a target placed in a phantom of the neck region, achieved with a circular array of antennas, with both simulations and experimental measurements.
1.N. R. Datta et al., “Local hyperthermia combined with radiotherapy and-/or chemotherapy: Recent advances and promises for the future,”, Cancer Treat. Rev., vol. 41, no. 9, pp. 742-53, 2015.
2. M. M. Paulides et al., “Status quo and directions in deep head and neck hyperthermia,” Radiat. Oncol., vol. 11, no. 21, pp. 809-21, 2016.


', ARRAY[]::text[], 'Expected duration: 6 person-months
